The main difference between this guns and the previous Colt series 70 is that the former incorporate a new firing pin block safety system, consisting of a series of internal levers and a plunger positively blocking the firing pin from moving until the trigger is pressed, hence eliminating the possibility of the gun going of if dropped onto a hard surface or struck hard. Other than that, the Colt series 70 and the 80 series do not differ too much from one another. The MAC-10 (Military Armament Corporation Model 10, officially the M-10) is a compact blowback operated machine pistol developed by Gordon Ingram in 1964.   It is chambered in either 45 ACP or 9mm.   A two-stage suppressor by Sonic’s was designed for the MAC-10, which not only abated the noise created, but made it easier to control on full automatic.
Military Armament Corporation (MAC), based in Powder Springs Georgia from 1970-1976 was the first company to commercially produce the MAC Model 10 (MAC-10).This is the company started by Gordon Ingram that designed and built the first MAC.    MAC marketed a number of different weapons, but the MAC-10 (chambered in 9 mm and later in.45 ACP) and the high cyclic rate (approx. 1600 rpm) MAC-11 (chambered in .380) were its mainstays.   MAC declared bankruptcy in 1976 and went out of business.
 
Military Armament Corporation in Stephenville, TX took the MAC design from the Powder Springs plant and redesigned the gun to be "better".  In short, they redesigned the trigger mechanism, the safety, and the stock for better fit and  reliability.

title: For Sale:  Norinco 1911A1, Customized, Used, .45 ACP
postcontent:
As the title says. Norinco 1911 that's been customized by a professional gunsmith. Gun is used. Slide has a major patina, and had some very minor pitting prior to being cleaned up. There is no rust to speak of now. It's a shooter, not a show piece. But you can certainly make it one. I had it customized by a friend and very competent gunsmith, who has been at his craft for many, many years. It started life as a basic GI configured 1911. It has several modifications, some of which are obvious in its appearance, such as the extended safety, Mainspring housing, etc. All added parts are either Wilson Combat or Colt. The gunsmith smoothed the action to near perfection; the slide feels like it's on ball bearings, and the trigger is arguably the best I've ever used. That's not an exaggeration to sell it, either. It's damn good. It's extremely accurate and ultimately reliable. It's just not pretty anymore. I'm selling it because it's been sitting in the safe not being used like it used to, and Xmas is creeping up, and I'm short on cash. So it goes. It'd be a good shooter or beater gun, or an excellent base for your custom 1911, if you want to go further with it. The allure of Norinco 1911s over others is that the steel used in the frame and slide is railroad steel, which is some of the toughest, if not the toughest on the market. I had to replace my gun smith's tool set because the steel ruined it. These 1911s also come reliable from the factory, so they make great base guns for a custom build. Hence why I chose it. The gun will come with a soft case, one Ed Brown magazine, a full box of Speer Gold Dots, and a Blackhawk Paddle Holster.
I will provide additional pictures upon request.
I need to sell it for extra cash for Xmas. $400 OBO. I will come to you if I get the full 400.

title: For Sale:  KelTec KSG 12ga Shotgun - TAN
postcontent: KSG 12ga dual-magazine-tube pump shotgun with tan furniture.The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of various accessories. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.
